AppImages are typically distributed as single files that can be downloaded from an application's website or a central repository like AppImageHub (https://appimage.github.io/).

chmod +x path/to/application.AppImage

./path/to/application.AppImage

wget "https://github.com/AppImage/appimaged/releases/download/continuous/appimaged-x86_64.AppImage"


////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

sudo apt install ansible

Configure the inventory file (/etc/ansible/hosts) with target hosts:

[webservers]
web1.example.com
web2.example.com

[dbservers]
db1.example.com
db2.example.com

Using Ansible for Package Management Update package cache on all hosts: - name: Update package cache
  
hosts: all
  become: yes
  tasks:
    - name: Update apt cache (Debian/Ubuntu)
      apt:
        update_cache: yes
      when: ansible_os_family == "Debian"


Install packages on specific host groups: - name: Install web server packages
  hosts: webservers
  become: yes
  tasks:
    - name: Install Apache and PHP
      package:
        name:
          - apache2
          - php
        state: present



Upgrade all packages on all hosts: - name: Upgrade all packages
  hosts: all
  become: yes
  tasks:
    - name: Upgrade packages (Debian/Ubuntu)
      apt:
        upgrade: dist
      when: ansible_os_family == "Debian"



Remove packages from specific hosts: - name: Remove unnecessary packages
  hosts: webservers
  become: yes
  tasks:
    - name: Remove FTP server
      package:
        name: vsftpd
        state: absent

